review: Do I think that following the Miracle Morning could change my life? Yes. Do I think this book could’ve been an infographic? Also yes. This was my firsDo I think that following the Miracle Morning could change my life? Yes. Do I think this book could’ve been an infographic? Also yes. This was my first foray into a true “Self Help” book. It was full of quotes, testimonials, and invitations to buy more classes/community/products. What more could I ask for! Elrod was at times painfully positive and self-promoting. I enjoyed hearing the perspective of someone who is so deeply invested in self-betterment and actualization. To Elrod, mediocrity is the ultimate fear. However, I cannot help but wonder what the opposing perspective is. Is there a healthy medium? One that sees and pursues potential yet also finds beauty in how things are — beauty in the ordinary/mediocre. Maybe I’ll figure that out during the meditation portion of my Miracle Morning. Ha! title: Writers & Lovers
author: King, Lily*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Strange to read a book that is so self-aware. A novel that is about writing a novel is that way I suppose. In one scene, she is describing why she lovStrange to read a book that is so self-aware. A novel that is about writing a novel is that way I suppose. In one scene, she is describing why she loves reading and writing. That some stories simply must be told! And the sheer wonder at the skill it takes to envelop someone in a world you created. The story itself (not just the writing, if that makes sense) made me appreciate the book so much more. There’s a passage where she describes how we often read books, and then ask questions that pull us out of the story. She asks how can we ask questions that push us further in “so they can feel everything the author tried so hard to create for them.” I often say I love reading books that teach me just as much about my own life as the life of the characters. But reading this made me stop and wonder if some books are meant to be read simply to know the characters and the world the author created more deeply. Overall, I really enjoyed this book. It started off a little slow for me but by the end I felt like I had read a true work of art! ...more
